nsNeighTable.name: nsNeighTable

tpAddress.name: tpAddress

portPhyX25AdminTable.name: portPhyX25AdminTable
portPhyX25AdminTable.description: This table contains Netlink Enterprise specific objects to manage an X25 port. Changing one of these parameters may take effect in the operating port immediately or may wait until the interface is restarted depending on the details of the implementation. Most of the objects in this read-write table have corresponding read-only objects in the portX25OperTable that return the current operating value. The operating values may be different from these configured values if a configured parameter was configured after the interface was started.

portPhyX25AdminEntry.name: portPhyX25AdminEntry
portPhyX25AdminEntry.description: A list of configured values for an X25 port.

portPhyX25AdminSpeed.name: portPhyX25AdminSpeed
portPhyX25AdminSpeed.description: This object defines the speed of the X25 port. The speed may only be set to one of a series of reasonable values, and if an attempt is made to set the speed to a value which is within the valid range but not equal to one of these values, the speed will be rounded up. If the connector type of the port is RS232, the port could be a standard port or a high speed port. If the port is a high speed RS232 port, the maximum valid speed is 256000. If the port is a standard RS232 port, the maximum valid speed is 64000 on the FRX4000/SS1840 and 19200 on all other products. It may be possible to set the speed of a standard RS232 port to a speed which is valid for a high speed RS232 port but invalid for a standard RS232 port. In this case, the port may not end up having the invalid speed. The default speed for a standard RS232 port on the FRX6000 is 19200.

portPhyX25AdminGenerateClock.name: portPhyX25AdminGenerateClock
portPhyX25AdminGenerateClock.description: Specifies whether the port will generate the clock necessary to synchronize traffic over the link.

portPhyX25AdminRcvClockFromDTE.name: portPhyX25AdminRcvClockFromDTE
portPhyX25AdminRcvClockFromDTE.description: This object defines whether the receive clock will be used from the DTE.

portPhyX25AdminDialOut.name: portPhyX25AdminDialOut
portPhyX25AdminDialOut.description: This flag indicates whether the port is connected to a dial modem, and whethter connections will be initiated through dial-in or dial-out calls.

portPhyX25AdminInactivityTimer.name: portPhyX25AdminInactivityTimer
portPhyX25AdminInactivityTimer.description: This timer defines in minutes, the period of inactivity allowed between calls. Once the timer expires, the port is disabled untill the next call is placed, if a Dial out port, or the Disconnect Timer expires, if a Dial in port. This variable is only meaningful if the port is a Dial port.

portPhyX25AdminDisconnectTimer.name: portPhyX25AdminDisconnectTimer
portPhyX25AdminDisconnectTimer.description: This timer defines, in seconds, the length of time a dial-in port will remain disabled after expiration of the InActivity Timer.

portPhyX25AdminSetupTimer.name: portPhyX25AdminSetupTimer
portPhyX25AdminSetupTimer.description: This timer determines the length of time, in seconds, that a response must be received by the port, after entering the Linkup state. If a response is not received, the port enters a Failed state.

portPhyX25AdminTrunkFlag.name: portPhyX25AdminTrunkFlag
portPhyX25AdminTrunkFlag.description: This flag, when set, indicates the port is associated with a network trunk group. It will be disabled/enabled if the network trunk is not operational.

portPhyX25AdminTrunkGroup.name: portPhyX25AdminTrunkGroup
portPhyX25AdminTrunkGroup.description: This variable contains a string of 8 bytes, with each byte indicating 8 ports on an RLP that may be a part of a trunk group. Since a TurboFrad has only 1 RLP, only the first byte is valid if the node is an FRX4000. Each port is represented by a single bit within the RLP byte. The bit position represents the port number...for example, if port 2 on RLP 0 was in a trunk group, the first byte of the string would contain x04 and all other bytes would be 0.

portPhyX25AdminRowStatus.name: portPhyX25AdminRowStatus
portPhyX25AdminRowStatus.description: This variable is used to manage the creation and deletion of conceptual rows in the portPhyX25AdminTable and follows the SNMPv2 RowStatus conventions by supporting the following values: - `active', which indicates that the conceptual row is available for use by the managed device, and which is supplied by a management station wishing to exercise an on-line update of the existing conceptual row. For a management protocol set operation, a genErr response is returned when the row does not exist. - `createAndGo', which is supplied by a management station wishing to create a new instance of a conceptual row and to have its status automatically set to active, making it available for use by the managed device. For a management protocol set operation, a genErr response is returned when the row already exists. - `destroy', which is supplied by a management station wishing to delete all of the instances associated with an existing conceptual row. Note that all of the above values may be specified in a management protocol set operation, and only the 'active' value will be returned in response to a management protocol retrieval operation. For a management protocol set operation, if other variable bindings are included in the same PDU, then a genErr response is returned.

portDLCIIncomingBe.name: portDLCIIncomingBe
portDLCIIncomingBe.description: The excess burst size is the maximum amount of incoming data in excess of the committed burst size that the network will try to transfer during the time interval determined by Bc/Cir on this DLCI.

portDLCIOutgoingBe.name: portDLCIOutgoingBe
portDLCIOutgoingBe.description: The excess burst size is the maximum amount of incoming data in excess of the committed burst size that the network will try to transfer during the time interval determined by Bc/Cir on this DLCI.

portDLCIBecnRecoveryCnt.name: portDLCIBecnRecoveryCnt

portDLCIRowStatus.name: portDLCIRowStatus

It may be possible to set the speed of a standard RS232 port to a speed which is valid for a high speed RS232 port but invalid for a standard RS232 port. In this case, the port may not end up having the invalid speed. The default speed for a standard RS232 port on the FRX6000 is 19200.

portVoiceAdminDTMF.description: The flag to enable, disable, or specify a time span over which DTMF (Dual Tone Multi Frequency) tones will be regenerated. 0 = pass tones transparently to the remote device. 1 = detect incoming tones and regenerate as received. 2-255 = regenerate tones for the specified seconds.

portVoiceAdminInterface.description: The type of interface (in conjunction with the Telephony Interface Type) that will be used by the Voice channel. portVoiceAdminTETimer.description: The delay at which the E&M 'E' lead follows the 'M' lead.

portVoiceAdminLevelIn.description: The local voice level into the voice port. This adjusts the sensitivity of the local voice channel to the signal from the attached device. The purpose of this is to match the voice channel dB level to the input signal. A more negative setting produces a higher input gain. If the level is reduced, the voice channel will be more sensitive to the input. This will also cause the voice output at the remote device to sound louder.

portVoiceAdminLevelOut.name: portVoiceAdminLevelOut
portVoiceAdminLevelOut.description: The local voice level out of the voice port. A more positive setting produces a higher volume.

portVoiceAdminCallTimer.name: portVoiceAdminCallTimer
portVoiceAdminCallTimer.description: The amount of time the node will wait for a response to a Call Connect or Call Clear request. portVoiceAdminHuntGroup.name: portVoiceAdminHuntGroup
portVoiceAdminHuntGroup.description: The hunt group that includes the voice channel.

portVoiceAdminLongDialPrefix.name: portVoiceAdminLongDialPrefix
portVoiceAdminLongDialPrefix.description: The character that will be required preceeding calls using the long call format. When the user at an attached device dials a long form number, it must be preceeded by the prefix character specified here.

portVoiceAdminSLTTimeout.name: portVoiceAdminSLTTimeout
portVoiceAdminSLTTimeout.description: The time the local port will wait before an actual fax transmission begins. If there is no fax tone when this timer expires, the connection will be terminated.

portVoiceAdminLinkDownBusy.name: portVoiceAdminLinkDownBusy
portVoiceAdminLinkDownBusy.description: This flag enables or disables automatic busy-out of channels when the link is down. When enabled, the system will automatically busy-out channels when the composite link is down. When disabled, channels remain on-hook when the link is down. If your application is connected to a PBX that can route calls to another alternate source based on an all busy condition, enable this so the PBX will recognize this condition and reroute the calls while the composite link is down.

portVoiceAdminFaxSupported.description: The flag to indicate whether or not faxes will be transmitted on the port. If no, all calls will be treated as voice. If yes, both voice and fax will be transmitted.

portVoiceAdminAutoDial.description: The flag to enable or disable the auto dial feature. Note that enabling this feature will disable the variable length dialing feature for this channel.

portVoiceAdminAutoPoll.name: portVoiceAdminAutoPoll

When enabled, the node periodically polls the destination. If the poll is not acknowledged, the node will busy-out the channel. This can be useful in situations where the destination is an emergency number that must always be available. If the destination does not answer the automatic poll, the busy-out condition will notify an attached PBX that the emergency call should be routed to another call routing device.

portVoiceAdminAutoPollTimer.name: portVoiceAdminAutoPollTimer
portVoiceAdminAutoPollTimer.description: The frequency with which an Auto Poll will be sent. This is applicable only when auto poll is enabled.

portVoiceAdminExtDigitsSource.name: portVoiceAdminExtDigitsSource

This is applicable only when the number of extended dial digits is greater than zero. When map is specified, extended digits are taken from the extended digits field in the map table. When user is specified, extended digits are taken from the user of attached equipment.

portVoiceAdminNumDigitsDelete.name: portVoiceAdminNumDigitsDelete
portVoiceAdminNumDigitsDelete.description: The number of leading dial digits that will be deleted before a dial string is forwarded. This is primarily used to delete leading dial digits that may be inserted by an attached PBX.

portVoiceAdminForwardDelay.name: portVoiceAdminForwardDelay
portVoiceAdminForwardDelay.description: The length of a pause that can be inserted in an extended dial string that is being forwarded. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended. When a comma is encountered in an extended digits string, the node will pause for the length of time specified here before additional extended digits are forwarded.

portVoiceAdminForwardedType.name: portVoiceAdminForwardedType

portVoiceAdminForwardedDigits.name: portVoiceAdminForwardedDigits
portVoiceAdminForwardedDigits.description: The flag indicating which dial digits, if any, to forward. If none, dial digits are not forwarded to the destination device when a call is initiated on this channel. If all, the dialed speed dial number and associated extended digits are forwarded to the destination device. If extended, only the extended digit string is forwarded.

portVoiceAdminMakeRatio.name: portVoiceAdminMakeRatio
portVoiceAdminMakeRatio.description: The make ratio of each digit pulse that is forwarded. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended and forwarded digit type is pulse.

portVoiceAdminBreakRatio.name: portVoiceAdminBreakRatio

Telephony Type Interface Type -------------- -------------- OPX (FXO) Loop Start SLT (FXS) Loop Start E&M 4W E&M, 4W E&M TE, 2W E&M, 2W E&M TE AC15 AC15A, AC15C

portVoiceOperTETimer.name: portVoiceOperTETimer
portVoiceOperTETimer.description: The delay at which the E&M 'E' lead follows the 'M' lead.

portVoiceOperLevelIn.name: portVoiceOperLevelIn
portVoiceOperLevelIn.description: The local voice level into the voice port. This adjusts the sensitivity of the local voice channel to the signal from the attached device. The purpose of this is to match the voice channel dB level to the input signal. A more negative setting produces a higher input gain. If the level is reduced, the voice channel will be more sensitive to the input. This will also cause the voice output at the remote device to sound louder.

portVoiceOperLevelOut.name: portVoiceOperLevelOut
portVoiceOperLevelOut.description: The local voice level out of the voice port. A more positive setting produces a higher volume.

portVoiceOperCallTimer.name: portVoiceOperCallTimer
portVoiceOperCallTimer.description: The amount of time the node will wait for a response to a Call Connect or Call Clear request. When the node issues a request, it will set a timer to the value configured here. If that timer expires with no response from the destination, the node will generate a busy tone.

portVoiceOperHuntGroup.name: portVoiceOperHuntGroup
portVoiceOperHuntGroup.description: The hunt group that includes the voice channel.

portVoiceOperLongDialPrefix.name: portVoiceOperLongDialPrefix
portVoiceOperLongDialPrefix.description: The character that will be required preceeding calls using the long call format. When the user at an attached device dials a long form number, it must be preceeded by the prefix character specified here.

portVoiceOperSLTTimeout.name: portVoiceOperSLTTimeout
portVoiceOperSLTTimeout.description: The time the local port will wait before an actual fax transmission begins. If there is no fax tone when this timer expires, the connection will be terminated.

portVoiceOperLinkDownBusy.name: portVoiceOperLinkDownBusy
portVoiceOperLinkDownBusy.description: This flag enables or disables automatic busy-out of channels when the link is down. When enabled, the system will automatically busy-out channels when the composite link is down. When disabled, channels remain on-hook when the link is down. If your application is connected to a PBX that can route calls to another alternate source based on an all busy condition, enable this so the PBX will recognize this condition and reroute the calls while the composite link is down.

portVoiceOperFaxSupported.name: portVoiceOperFaxSupported
portVoiceOperFaxSupported.description: The flag to indicate whether or not faxes will be transmitted on the port. If no, all calls will be treated as voice. If yes, both voice and fax will be transmitted.

portVoiceOperTelephonyType.name: portVoiceOperTelephonyType
portVoiceOperTelephonyType.description: The type of interface (in conjunction with the Interface Type) that will be used by the Voice channel. This requires rebooting for the change to take effect. Telephony Type Interface Type -------------- -------------- OPX (FXO) Loop Start SLT (FXS) Loop Start E&M 4W E&M, 4W E&M TE, 2W E&M, 2W E&M TE AC15 AC15A, AC15C

portVoiceOperDialTimer.name: portVoiceOperDialTimer
portVoiceOperDialTimer.description: The delay the node will use to determine when variable length dialing is complete. (Variable length dialing allows the user to place a call without entering the configured number of digits for the speed dial number.)

portVoiceOperAutoDial.name: portVoiceOperAutoDial
portVoiceOperAutoDial.description: The flag to enable or disable the auto dial feature. Note that enabling this feature will disable the variable length dialing feature for this channel.

portVoiceOperSuppression.name: portVoiceOperSuppression
portVoiceOperSuppression.description: The silence suppression level. A larger silence suppression level allows more data channels to operate simultaneously with the voice channels.

portVoiceOperAutoDialNumber.name: portVoiceOperAutoDialNumber
portVoiceOperAutoDialNumber.description: The number to which the node will attempt to connect when the handset attached to this port is taken off-hook. This is applicable only when the Auto Dial feature is enabled.

portVoiceOperAutoPoll.name: portVoiceOperAutoPoll
portVoiceOperAutoPoll.description: The flag to enable or disable auto polling. This is applicable only when the Auto Dial feature is enabled. When enabled, the node periodically polls the destination. If the poll is not acknowledged, the node will busy-out the channel. This can be useful in situations where the destination is an emergency number that must always be available. If the destination does not answer the automatic poll, the busy-out condition will notify an attached PBX that the emergency call should be routed to another call routing device.

portVoiceOperAutoPollTimer.name: portVoiceOperAutoPollTimer
portVoiceOperAutoPollTimer.description: The frequency with which an Auto Poll will be sent. This is applicable only when auto poll is enabled.

portVoiceOperExtDigitsSource.name: portVoiceOperExtDigitsSource
portVoiceOperExtDigitsSource.description: The source of the extended digits when the user of attached equipment dials a speed dial number. This is applicable only when the number of extended dial digits is greater than zero. When map is specified, extended digits are taken from the extended digits field in the map table. When user is specified, extended digits are taken from the user of attached equipment.

portVoiceOperNumDigitsDelete.name: portVoiceOperNumDigitsDelete
portVoiceOperNumDigitsDelete.description: The number of leading dial digits that will be deleted before a dial string is forwarded. This is primarily used to delete leading dial digits that may be inserted by an attached PBX.

portVoiceOperForwardDelay.name: portVoiceOperForwardDelay
portVoiceOperForwardDelay.description: The length of a pause that can be inserted in an extended dial string that is being forwarded. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended. When a comma is encountered in an extended digits string, the node will pause for the length of time specified here before additional extended digits are forwarded.

portVoiceOperForwardedType.name: portVoiceOperForwardedType
portVoiceOperForwardedType.description: The method how the dial digits will be forwarded. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended.

portVoiceOperForwardedDigits.name: portVoiceOperForwardedDigits
portVoiceOperForwardedDigits.description: The flag indicating which dial digits, if any, to forward. If none, dial digits are not forwarded to the destination device when a call is initiated on this channel. If all, the dialed speed dial number and associated extended digits are forwarded to the destination device. If extended, only the extended digit string is forwarded.

portVoiceOperMakeRatio.name: portVoiceOperMakeRatio
portVoiceOperMakeRatio.description: The make ratio of each digit pulse that is forwarded. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended and forwarded digit type is pulse.

portVoiceOperBreakRatio.name: portVoiceOperBreakRatio
portVoiceOperBreakRatio.description: The break ratio of each digit pulse that is forwarded. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended and forwarded digit type is pulse.

portVoiceOperDTMFOnDuration.name: portVoiceOperDTMFOnDuration
portVoiceOperDTMFOnDuration.description: The length of a tone that will be used to produce a single DTMF digit. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended and forwarded digit type is DTMF.

portVoiceOperDTMFOffDuration.name: portVoiceOperDTMFOffDuration
portVoiceOperDTMFOffDuration.description: The length of silence between DTMF tones in a dial digit string. This is applicable only when forwarded output digits is all or extended and forwarded digit type is DTMF.

portVoiceOperToneType.name: portVoiceOperToneType
portVoiceOperToneType.description: The tone type to detect/regenerate for forwarding DTMF/MF.

nlIfTable.name: nlIfTable
nlIfTable.description: A Table to describe each interface on a node. This table is indexed by RLP and Port number and can be used to identify the corresponding MIB-II ifIndex of a Port as well as additional port information maintained by Netlink.

nlIfEntry.name: nlIfEntry
nlIfEntry.description: An Interface entry containing objects relating to interfaces.

nlIfRlp.name: nlIfRlp
nlIfRlp.description: The RLP number on the node. RLP numbers 1-8 are Physical RLP cards, and RLP number 250, 251 and 252 define IP, IPX and LLC2 interfaces respectively.

nlIfPort.name: nlIfPort
nlIfPort.description: The Port number on the RLP. Port numbers 1-8 are known to be physical ports, and 9-64 are logical ports. If the RLP number identifies an IP, IPX or LLC2 interface, then the port number can be 1-257 (IP), 1-64 (IPX), or 1-96 (LLC2).

nlIfIndex.name: nlIfIndex
nlIfIndex.description: The associated index into the MIB-II ifTable for this port

nlIfTableIndex.name: nlIfTableIndex
nlIfTableIndex.description: The associated index into an enterprise table used to describe additional information for this port. See nlIfTableOid as the pointer to the actual table.

nlIfTableOid.name: nlIfTableOid
nlIfTableOid.description: The OID of the table Entry that contains additional information about this port. The OID will point to a specific table depending on the type of port.

nlIfConnectorType.name: nlIfConnectorType
nlIfConnectorType.description: The physical connector type used for this port. Valid for ports 1-8 only.

nlIfPortStatus.name: nlIfPortStatus
nlIfPortStatus.description: The status of this port state. Valid for ports 1-64 only.

nlIfPhyPort.name: nlIfPhyPort
nlIfPhyPort.description: The Underlying Physical Port number on the RLP of this logical port. Port numbers 1-8 are valid, but this field is only applicable if the nlIfPort field is 9-64.

nlIfLlc2LANTable.name: nlIfLlc2LANTable
nlIfLlc2LANTable.description: A Table to define LLC2 interfaces over LAN.

nlIfLlc2LANEntry.name: nlIfLlc2LANEntry
nlIfLlc2LANEntry.description: An LLC2 LAN Interface entry containing objects relating to LLC2 LAN interfaces.

nlIfLlc2LANRlp.name: nlIfLlc2LANRlp
nlIfLlc2LANRlp.description: The RLP number on the node. For LLC2 LAN interfaces, this must be 252.

nlIfLlc2LANPort.name: nlIfLlc2LANPort
nlIfLlc2LANPort.description: The Port number on the RLP. For LLC2 LAN interfaces, this corresponds to the LAN card number.

nlIfLlc2LANType.name: nlIfLlc2LANType
nlIfLlc2LANType.description: The type of the LLC2 interface- either ethernet or token ring.

nlIfLlc2LANCard.name: nlIfLlc2LANCard
nlIfLlc2LANCard.description: The LAN card that the LLC2 interface is running on.

nlIfLlc2LANID.name: nlIfLlc2LANID
nlIfLlc2LANID.description: Valid only if the type of the LLC2 LAN interface is token ring. Identifies the token ring adapter to the network.

nlIfLlc2LANRowStatus.name: nlIfLlc2LANRowStatus
nlIfLlc2LANRowStatus.description: This variable is used to manage the creation and deletion of conceptual rows in the nlIfLlc2LANTable and follows the SNMPv2 RowStatus conventions by supporting the following values: - `active', which indicates that the conceptual row is available for use by the managed device. For a management protocol set operation, a genErr response is returned when the row does not exist. - `createAndGo', which is supplied by a management station wishing to create a new instance of a conceptual row and to have its status automatically set to active, making it available for use by the managed device. For a management protocol set operation, a genErr response is returned when the row already exists. - `destroy', which is supplied by a management station wishing to delete all of the instances associated with an existing conceptual row. Note that all of the above values may be specified in a management protocol set operation, and only the 'active' value will be returned in response to a management protocol retrieval operation. For a management protocol set operation, if other variable bindings are included in the same PDU, then a genErr response is returned.

nlIfLlc2LANPriority.name: nlIfLlc2LANPriority
nlIfLlc2LANPriority.description: Interface priority- allows setting a priority for traffic within the node. The higher the number, the higher the priority relative to other intra-nodal traffic.

nlIfLlc2FrTable.name: nlIfLlc2FrTable
nlIfLlc2FrTable.description: A Table to define LLC2 interfaces over Frame Relay.

nlIfLlc2FrEntry.name: nlIfLlc2FrEntry
nlIfLlc2FrEntry.description: An LLC2 FR Interface entry containing objects relating to LLC2 FR interfaces.

nlIfLlc2FrRlp.name: nlIfLlc2FrRlp
nlIfLlc2FrRlp.description: The RLP number on the node.

nlIfLlc2FrPort.name: nlIfLlc2FrPort
nlIfLlc2FrPort.description: The Port number on the RLP. Port numbers 1-8 are known to be physical ports, and channels are 193-241.

nlIfLlc2FrDLCI.name: nlIfLlc2FrDLCI
nlIfLlc2FrDLCI.description: The DLCI number used to identify the entry in the table. The range is 16-991.

nlIfLlc2FrFormat.name: nlIfLlc2FrFormat
nlIfLlc2FrFormat.description: The RFC1490 encapsulation method used for LLC2 traffic.

nlIfLlc2FrPriority.name: nlIfLlc2FrPriority
nlIfLlc2FrPriority.description: Interface priority- allows setting a priority for traffic within the node. The higher the number, the higher the priority relative to other intra-nodal traffic.

nlIfLlc2FrBAG.name: nlIfLlc2FrBAG
nlIfLlc2FrBAG.description: Assigns the interface to one of sixteen groups whose parameters regulate bandwidth usage.

nlIfLlc2FrHostMACAddress.name: nlIfLlc2FrHostMACAddress
nlIfLlc2FrHostMACAddress.description: The MAC address of the host or workstation to which the remote device needs to connect. Valid only if the format is native-llc2.

nlIfLlc2FrSessionType.name: nlIfLlc2FrSessionType
nlIfLlc2FrSessionType.description: If originated, means that LLC2 connects from the configured Host MAC address can use this interface. If terminated, connections to the configured address can use this interface. Valid only if the format is native-llc2.

nlIfLlc2FrLANID.name: nlIfLlc2FrLANID

ipxServConfigEntry.description: Each entry corresponds to one instance of IPX Static Routing on the system

ipxServConfigServiceType.name: ipxServConfigServiceType
ipxServConfigServiceType.description: The Service Type, a SAP service code

ipxServConfigServName.description: The Sercice Name, identifies a specific server in the IPX network.

ipxServConfigServNetworkAddress.description: The IPX network number portion of the IPX address of the server identified by ServName

ipxServConfigServNodeAddress.name: ipxServConfigServNodeAddress
ipxServConfigServNodeAddress.description: The node portion of the IPX address of the service

ipxServConfigServSocketNumber.name: ipxServConfigServSocketNumber
ipxServConfigServSocketNumber.description: The socket portion of the IPX address of the service

ipxServConfigInterveningNetworks.description: The number of routers that a packet must pass through t reach the server

ipxServConfigGatewayAddress.description: The node address of the router thar will forward a packet

ipxServConfigInterface.name: ipxServConfigInterface
ipxServConfigInterface.description: The IPX network number assigned to the interface used to send packets that are destined for this server

ipxInterfaceBlockedPortFlag.description: This flag causes the IPX interface to be enabled (N) or disabled (Y) at node IPL. The port will remain in that state until this parameter is changed

ipxInterfaceType.name: ipxInterfaceType
ipxInterfaceType.description: The interface type. 802.5 is not valid on FRX4000

ipxInterfaceFrameType.description: The frame type - depends on the interfece type. Valid combinations are: Ethernet, 802.5 - typeII, raw, llc, snap Frame relay, X25 - typeII

ipxInterfaceMaxTransUnit.name: ipxInterfaceMaxTransUnit
ipxInterfaceMaxTransUnit.description: Maximum frame size that can be transmitted or received over the IPX interface.: Valid ranges are: Ethernet - (45-1518) 802.5 - (48-4096) Frame relay, X25 - (31-4096)

ipxInterfaceNetworkAddress.name: ipxInterfaceNetworkAddress
ipxInterfaceNetworkAddress.description: Identifies the local interface to the Novell Network

ipxInterfaceBandwidthAllocGroup.name: ipxInterfaceBandwidthAllocGroup
ipxInterfaceBandwidthAllocGroup.description: Assigns the IPX interface to one of sixteen groups whose parameters regulate bandwidth usage

ipxInterfacePortDiagEnabled.name: ipxInterfacePortDiagEnabled
ipxInterfacePortDiagEnabled.description: Enables/Disables the IPX interface's ability to handle Novell diagonistics packets

ipxInterfaceNetBIOSEnabled.name: ipxInterfaceNetBIOSEnabled
ipxInterfaceNetBIOSEnabled.description: Determines whether Novell-encapsulated NetBIOS frames received on the interface will be processed

ipxInterfaceNetBIOSHops.name: ipxInterfaceNetBIOSHops
ipxInterfaceNetBIOSHops.description: Maximum number of hops allowed for routing a Novell-encapsulated NetBIOS frame

ipxInterfacePeriodicRIPEnabled.name: ipxInterfacePeriodicRIPEnabled
ipxInterfacePeriodicRIPEnabled.description: Determines whether the node will originate periodic IPX Routing Information Protocol messages from this interface to inform the network that the route through this interface is viable

ipxInterfacePeriodicRIPTimer.name: ipxInterfacePeriodicRIPTimer
ipxInterfacePeriodicRIPTimer.description: This is the interval between the periodic IPX RIP broadcasts from this interface

ipxInterfacePeriodicSAPEnabled.name: ipxInterfacePeriodicSAPEnabled

ipxInterfacePeriodicSAPTimer.name: ipxInterfacePeriodicSAPTimer

ipxInterfaceSAPEnabled.name: ipxInterfaceSAPEnabled
ipxInterfaceSAPEnabled.description: Determines whether the interface will support SAP or not

ipxInterfaceSAPAgeTimer.name: ipxInterfaceSAPAgeTimer

ipxInterfaceWanEnabled.name: ipxInterfaceWanEnabled

ipxInterfaceSVCRetryTimer.name: ipxInterfaceSVCRetryTimer
ipxInterfaceSVCRetryTimer.description: The frequency with which calls will be placed to try to establish a connection .. Valid only for type X.25

ipxNodeDefaultConfigRIPSAPGap.name: ipxNodeDefaultConfigRIPSAPGap
ipxNodeDefaultConfigRIPSAPGap.description: The minimum delay between consecutive RIP and SAP transmissions

ipxNodeDefaultConfigRouterName.description: An unique identifier within the IPX network

nlIfIpTable.description: A Table to define IP interfaces over frame relay, X.25, or LAN (ethernet, 802.3, 802.5).

nlIfIpEntry.name: nlIfIpEntry
nlIfIpEntry.description: An IP Interface entry containing objects relating to IP interfaces.

nlIfIpInterface.name: nlIfIpInterface
nlIfIpInterface.description: The interface number which uniquely identifies the interface to which this entry is applicable. The interface identified by a particular value of this number is NOT the same interface as defined by the same value of ifIndex.

nlIfIpMtu.name: nlIfIpMtu
nlIfIpMtu.description: The maximum size (in bytes) of the data field that can be used to encapsulate an IP datagram for transmission over the interface. If the interface type is LAN based, then the maximum size value cannot exceed 1500.

nlIfIpNetworkMask.description: The mask used during routing to determine the portion of the address associated with the network.

nlIfIpRouteMetric.description: The number of network hops (network gateways in the overall path over the internet) associated with this interface.

nlIfIpICMPAddRoutes.description: The flag which indicates whether IP may add routes obtained by ICMP, whose error and control function is used to send re-direction options back to the source if problems are discovered.

nlIfIpRIPDeltaUpdates.description: The frequency with which RIP messages will be sent to every neighbor node, containing any changes to the routing table that occurred since the last full update.

nlIfIpRIPFullUpdates.name: nlIfIpRIPFullUpdates

voiceSpeedDialRowStatus.description: This variable is used to manage the creation and deletion of conceptual rows in the voiceSpeedDialTable and follows the SNMPv2 RowStatus conventions by supporting the following values: - `active', which indicates that the conceptual row is available for use by the managed device. For a management protocol set operation, a genErr response is returned when the row does not exist. - `createAndGo', which is supplied by a management station wishing to create a new instance of a conceptual row and to have its status automatically set to active, making it available for use by the managed device. For a management protocol set operation, a genErr response is returned when the row already exists. - `destroy', which is supplied by a management station wishing to delete all of the instances associated with an existing conceptual row. Note that all of the above values may be specified in a management protocol set operation, and only the 'active' value will be returned in response to a management protocol retrieval operation. For a management protocol set operation, if other variable bindings are included in the same PDU, then a genErr response is returned.
